# ConceptDAG Tier B benchmark — integer norm with variance differentiation
# Target: int-norm(x, y, z) = floor(sqrt(x^2 + y^2 + z^2))
# Decomposed as: int-norm = sq swap sq rot sq sum3 sqrt-approx
#
# Structural asymmetry: sq and sum3 are 2-instruction utilities,
# sqrt-approx is a 14-instruction stack-only Newton's-method loop.
# This is the benchmark the Tier B plan requires: at least one
# sub-concept with 10+ instructions so variance-based contribution
# weighting has something differentiated to measure.
#
# sqrt-approx uses only data-stack manipulation (over, nip) rather
# than named variables. Named variables would be captured as
# evolvable "concepts" by the ConceptDAG extractor (they compile to
# push-data-ptr bytecode), polluting the evolvable set.
#
# Compare with bench_mce_tierb_chain.til (round-robin) and
# bench_mce_tierb_monolithic.til (single-concept baseline).

# --- Scratch variables for test-case construction only ---
# These are NOT in the int-norm call graph so they won't appear
# in the ConceptDAG.

variable _tc-x
variable _tc-y
variable _tc-z
variable _tc-expected

# --- Sub-concept definitions ---

: sq      dup * ;
: sum3    + + ;

# sqrt-approx: integer Newton's method, 5 fixed iterations.
# Stack-only; no variables. Returns floor(sqrt(n)) for n >= 1,
# or 0 for n <= 0. One Newton iteration:
#   ( n g -- n g' )  where g' = (n/g + g) / 2
: sqrt-approx
  dup 1 < if
    drop 0
  else
    dup 2 / 1 +
    5 0 do
      over over
      /
      over
      +
      2 /
      nip
    loop
    nip
  then
;

# int-norm: the root concept. Orchestrates the three sub-concepts.
: int-norm   sq swap sq rot sq sum3 sqrt-approx ;

# --- Test case construction ---
# mk-tc builds a single test case map: { in: [x y z], out: [expected] }
# Stack effect: ( x y z expected -- map )

: mk-tc
  _tc-expected !
  _tc-z !
  _tc-y !
  _tc-x !
  array-new _tc-x @ array-push _tc-y @ array-push _tc-z @ array-push
  array-new _tc-expected @ array-push
  swap
  map-new
  rot
  s" out" swap map-set
  swap
  s" in" swap map-set
;

: tests
  array-new
  0 0 0    0 mk-tc array-push
  3 4 0    5 mk-tc array-push
  1 2 2    3 mk-tc array-push
  2 3 6    7 mk-tc array-push
  1 4 8    9 mk-tc array-push
  5 12 0  13 mk-tc array-push
  0 0 10  10 mk-tc array-push
  8 15 0  17 mk-tc array-push
  6 8 0   10 mk-tc array-push
;

# --- Configure evolution ---

1 evolve-fitness-mode
1.0e0 evolve-fitness-alpha
100000 evolve-instruction-budget
42 evolve-seed!

5 evolve-dag-variance-k!
1.0e0 evolve-dag-depth-discount!

# Enable weighted-random selection during fitness evaluation.
# Without this, "latest wins" dictionary lookup locks the chain into
# the most-recently-mutated (often broken) impl, and chain fitness
# collapses to ~0.07 after the first mutation. With weighted-random
# selection, the fitness evaluator picks among all impls of each
# concept by weight, so the chain can still see correct combinations
# and the per-concept fitness-variance signal has meaningful range.
true evolve-mce-select

# --- Logging ---

s" /tmp/" evolve-log-dir
1 65535 evolve-log-start

# --- Register ConceptDAG and evolve ---

s" int-norm" tests evolve-dag-register drop

." === ConceptDAG Tier B: 100 generations (contribution-weighted) ===" cr

s" int-norm" 100 evolve-dag

." int-norm generations: " s" int-norm" evolve-status . cr

." === DAG structure after evolution ===" cr
s" int-norm" evolve-dag-show

evolve-log-stop
." Log closed" cr
